{# Grand jury subpoena boilerplate (federal).

   Drafted as STARTING POINT for the AUSA. Recupero does not have
   subpoena authority — this is the document the AUSA will edit and
   place under their own letterhead before serving on the VASP /
   exchange.

   Required Jinja context:
     - case_id, generated_at
     - victim: name
     - perpetrator: exchange_name, exchange_legal_name, exchange_address,
       deposit_address, total_received_usd
     - investigator: name, organization, email (carrying counsel — for
       AUSA contact only)
     - tx_evidence: list of {tx_hash, block_time, amount_usd, explorer_url}
#}<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Grand Jury Subpoena — Draft for AUSA Review — Case {{ case_id }}</title>
{% include "_styles.html.j2" %}
</head>
<body>

<section class="cover">
  <div class="cover-letterhead">
    <div class="cover-wordmark">
      Recupero
      <span class="tagline">Investigation Services</span>
    </div>
    <div class="cover-letterhead-right">
      <div class="confidential">DRAFT — For AUSA Review &amp; Issuance Only</div>
      <div class="date">{{ generated_at }} UTC</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="cover-title-block">
    <div class="cover-eyebrow">Grand Jury Subpoena (Duces Tecum) — Draft</div>
    <h1>Subpoena to<br/>{{ perpetrator.exchange_name }}</h1>
    <p class="cover-subtitle">
      Boilerplate document compendium to expedite a grand jury
      subpoena duces tecum, pursuant to Rule 17(c) of the Federal
      Rules of Criminal Procedure, addressed to
      {{ perpetrator.exchange_legal_name|default(perpetrator.exchange_name) }}.
      Recupero has no subpoena authority — this document is provided to
      assist the AUSA's drafting process. The Assistant United States
      Attorney must issue the final subpoena on government letterhead.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="content">

<h2>1. Subpoena Recipient</h2>
<p>
{{ perpetrator.exchange_legal_name|default(perpetrator.exchange_name) }}<br/>
Registered Agent for Service of Process:
{{ perpetrator.registered_agent|default("[TODO: look up registered agent / general counsel address]") }}<br/>
{{ perpetrator.exchange_address|default("[TODO: company address]") }}
</p>

<h2>2. Subject of the Subpoena</h2>
<p>
The recipient is hereby commanded, pursuant to Rule 17(c) of the
Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure, to produce the records
described below to the grand jury of the
{{ jurisdiction|default("[TODO: judicial district]") }} sitting at
{{ courthouse|default("[TODO: courthouse address]") }} on or before
{{ response_date|default("[TODO: 30-day return date]") }}.
</p>

<h2>3. Records Demanded</h2>
<p>For the period commencing {{ records_start_date|default("[TODO: first deposit date]") }}
through the date of service of this subpoena, the recipient is
commanded to produce the following:</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>Customer account identification</strong> for the customer
    account or accounts associated with the following digital-asset
    deposit address:
    <p class="mono">{{ perpetrator.deposit_address }}</p>
    including the customer's full legal name, all known aliases,
    date of birth, taxpayer identification number (where collected),
    primary and secondary residence and mailing addresses, primary
    and secondary email addresses, primary and secondary phone
    numbers, and the full set of government-issued identification
    documents collected during the recipient's Customer Identification
    Program / Know Your Customer process, including front and reverse
    of each identification document.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Account history and balance records:</strong> all account
    opening documents (including any source-of-funds attestations,
    self-certification forms, and risk-rating worksheets); all
    statements of account; any compliance-team annotations, internal
    memoranda, or escalation tickets referencing this account or any
    address associated with it; and any current and historical account
    balances by asset.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Transaction records:</strong> all on-chain deposits and
    withdrawals against the account (including transaction hash,
    counterparty address, asset, amount, and timestamp); all
    off-platform transfers and internal transfers between the account
    and other recipient-controlled accounts; and all fiat on-ramp and
    off-ramp transactions associated with the account, including
    bank wires (originating institution, account number, ABA / SWIFT
    routing, amount, and date).
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Access and device records:</strong> all IP addresses
    logged for sessions accessing the account, with full timestamps;
    all device fingerprints, user-agent strings, and other
    device-level identifiers recorded by the recipient's anti-fraud
    systems; and all multi-factor authentication device records and
    enrollment events.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Communications:</strong> all communications between the
    recipient's customer-support, compliance, or fraud teams and the
    account holder, including chat transcripts, email correspondence,
    support tickets, and recorded telephone calls. To the extent that
    the recipient retains a record of any internal escalation,
    review, or hold placed on the account, those records are also
    demanded.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Subsequent disposition:</strong> for any digital assets
    withdrawn from the account to an on-chain destination, the
    destination address and transaction hash. For any digital assets
    transferred internally to another recipient-controlled account,
    the receiving account identifier and all paragraph (1) records
    for that receiving account.
  </li>
</ol>

<h2>4. Predicate On-Chain Evidence</h2>
<p>
The following on-chain transaction records constitute the
investigation's evidentiary basis for connecting the deposit
address to the criminal conduct under investigation:
</p>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Tx Hash</th><th>Block Time (UTC)</th><th>USD Amount</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for tx in tx_evidence %}
    <tr>
      <td class="mono">{{ tx.tx_hash }}</td>
      <td>{{ tx.block_time }}</td>
      <td>{{ tx.amount_usd }}</td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>5. Mode of Production</h2>
<p>
Records produced in response to this subpoena shall be transmitted
in their native electronic format where reasonably available;
PDF reproductions are acceptable where native format is impractical.
Production shall be made directly to the AUSA listed in Section 7,
not to the grand jury reporter, and shall include a certification
of authenticity under Federal Rule of Evidence 902(11).
</p>

<h2>6. Confidentiality Direction</h2>
<p>
Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. § 2705(b), and on a separate motion or order
to be obtained by the AUSA, the recipient is requested NOT to
notify the affected customer of the existence of this subpoena
or of the substance of its compliance, for a period of
{{ secrecy_period_days|default(90) }} days from service or until
further order of the court. The recipient is reminded that, absent
such order, the customer may be entitled to notice.
</p>

<h2>7. Issuing Authority and Point of Contact</h2>
<p>
<strong>[TO BE COMPLETED BY AUSA]</strong>
</p>
<p>
Name of Assistant United States Attorney:<br/>
Office:<br/>
Address:<br/>
Telephone:<br/>
Email:<br/>
</p>

<p><em>Investigation contact (non-government, for AUSA's reference only):</em></p>
<p>
{{ investigator.name }}<br/>
{{ investigator.organization }}<br/>
{{ investigator.email }}
</p>

</section>
</body>
</html>
